problems.problem:
Let there be two coaxial conducting cylinders with vacuum between them. The radius of the inner cylinder is $a$ and the inner radius of the outer cylinder is $b$, as shown in the figure below. The outer cylinder, called the anode, may be given a positive potential $V$ relative to the inner cylinder. A uniform magnetic field $B$ parallel to the cylinder axis, directed out of the plane of the figure, is also present. Induced charges in the conductors are neglected. Electrons of mass $m$ and charge $-q$ are released at the surface of the inner cylinder.
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{ipho2}
    \end{center}
    \begin{anum}
        \item Initially, $B=0$, but the outer cylinder is charged to the potential $V$. Electrons are released from rest from the inner cylinder. What are the velocities of the electrons when they reach the outer cylinder?
        \item Now $V = 0$, but now the magnetic field $B$ is present. An electron starts out with an initial velocity $v_0$ in the radial direction. For magnetic fields larger than a critical value $B_c$ the electron will not reach the anode. Determine $B_c$.
        \item Now, both $V$ and $B$ are present. The magnetic field will give the electron a non-zero angular momentum $L$ with respect to the cylinder axis. Write down an equation for the rate of change $dL/dt$ of the angular momentum. Show that this equation implies that $$L-kqBr^2$$ is constant during the motion, where $k$ is some number. Here $r$ is the distance from the cylinders' axes. Find $k$.
        \item Consider an electron, released from the inner cylinder with negligible velocity, that does not reach the anode, but has a maximal distance from the cylinder axis equal to $r_m$. Determine the speed $v$ at the point where the radial distance is maximal, in terms of $r_m$.
        \item For $B$ larger than a critical magnetic field $B_c$, an electron, released with negligible velocity, will not reach the anode. Determine $B_c$.
    \end{anum}

problems.solution:
\begin{anum}
        \item By conservation of energy, $$\frac12mv^2=qV\Rightarrow v=\boxed{\sqrt{\frac{2qV}{m}}}$$
        \item The electrons will move in circles. If the magnetic field strength is too strong, the electron's path will curve back too quickly. The critical case is shown below.\begin{center}
            \includegraphics[scale=0.2]{crucial}
        \end{center}
        The critical radius of the orbit is given by the equation $$r+\sqrt{r^2+a^2}=b\Rightarrow r=\frac{b^2-a^2}{2b}$$
        And since $r=mv/qB_c$, we solve to get $$B_c=\boxed{\frac{2mvb}{q(b^2-a^2)}}$$
        \item Notice that the force exerted by the electric field is radial, as well as the magnetic force from the azimuthal component of velocity $(v_\phi \hat{\phi}\times \mathbf B)$. Thus, $$\frac{dL}{dt}=qv_rBr=qBr\frac{dr}{dt}$$and integrating yields $k=\boxed{1/2}$. 
        \item When the radial distance is maximal, the speed is purely in the azimuthal direction, so $L=mvr_m$. The electron is released with initially no velocity, so in using the conserved quantity from part (c) we get $$-\frac12qBa^2=mvr_m-\frac12qBr_m^2\Rightarrow v=\boxed{\frac{qB(r_m^2-a^2)}{2mr_m}}$$
        \item Since $\mathbf B$ cannot do any work, the velocity of the electron when it is about to hit the anode is always given by that in part (a). We want to match this velocity to the crucial velocity in part (d) with $r_m=b$. Solving for $B_c$, $$\sqrt{\frac{2qV}{m}}=\frac{qB_c(b^2-a^2)}{2mb}\Rightarrow B_c=\boxed{\frac{2b}{b^2-a^2}\sqrt{\frac{2mV}{q}}}$$
    \end{anum}
